observations.recommendation:
We recommended the Management to:

   a. require the GSO to reflect in the RPCPPE the actual  PPE  counted  and reconciliation between the records of the MA and GSO be undertaken and effect the necessary adjustments in the  accounting  books  to  fairly present the said accounts in the financial statements;

   b. perform One-Time Cleansing of PPE as prescribed in COA Circular  2020-006 to be able to establish PPE balances that  are  verifiable  as  to existence, condition and accountability;

   c. require the GSO to maintain the pertinent reports and property records of Road Networks to be able to provide reliable basis on the amounts presented in the financial statements;

   d. require Municipal Accountant to disclose in the Notes to FS the road network system;

   e. dispose the unserviceable properties and  the  corresponding  cost  or value be dropped from the books of accounts;

   f. direct the Municipal Accountant to identify possible items that  needs to be excluded from the PPE account and  make  proper  adjustments  if deemed necessary;


   g. ensure that an ICS is on file or had been prepared by the  GSO  before these semi-expendable assets are removed from PPE  account  to  ensure control and accountability; and

   h. require the  MEO  to  timely  submit  to  the  Accounting  Office  the necessary documents for the recording of construction in  progress  so as to correctly reflect the PPE balance.

We recommended that Management:


     a. require the establishment of a  separate  General  Services  Office (GSO) and stock room for proper storage of  items  of  inventories. Consider hiring of additional personnel to perform the  duties  and functions of the GSO, and  require  the  coordination  between  the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer’s  Office  towards the full  implementation  of  the  perpetual  inventory  method  in recording of supplies and materials;


     b. require the Inventory Committee and the  Office  of  the  Municipal Accountant to prioritize the reconciliation between  the  Inventory accounts balances per books and per RPCI;


     c. require the MGSO to maintain and submit the Summary of Supplies and Materials Issued (SSMI) together with the corresponding Requisition and Issue Slip (RIS) for the issued  supplies/goods,  and maintain stock cards for each item of Inventory to ensure proper  accounting and promote better control in the receipt and issuance of supplies;  and

     d.  ensure  that  semestral  count  of  Inventory  items  is  promptly conducted and the corresponding report is submitted on time to  the Audit Team.

We recommended that Management require the Municipal Accountant to:


     i) Exert utmost efforts  in  retrieving  the  necessary  documents  to support the accuracy and validity of the  fund  transfers  recorded under the Due to NGAs account amounting to ₱277,000.90, and provide adequate disclosure in the notes to financial statements;


    ii) prepare  the  necessary  accounting/adjusting  journal  entries  to recognize the aforementioned completed projects in their respective PPE accounts in the GF books;


   iii) ensure proper recording of expenditures and  liquidation  of  trust funds, closing entries and transfer of completed  PPEs  from  Trust Fund to General Fund in the books of accounts; and


    iv) fully utilize  the  funds  granted  by  the  national  agencies  to effectively and timely extend to the constituents the  benefits  of the projects.

We recommended that Management:

       a.   require the Market Administrator and the Municipal Treasurer  to strictly implement and enforce  the  provisions  embodied  in  the foregoing municipal tax ordinances, particularly those relating to the collection of market fees  and  cancellation  of  lease  right and/or eviction of delinquent stallholders;


       b.    adopt  sterner  and  stricter  strategies  to   intensify   its collection  efforts  and  forestall  the  undue  accumulation   of uncollected market stall rentals;


       c.    resort  to  other  remedies  available  to  collect  its   long outstanding uncollected market stall rental;


       d.   require the Municipal Accountant to take  up  in  the  books  of accounts the uncollected market stall rental fees that are deemed realizable;


       e.   initiate  a  comprehensive  review  of  the  operations  of  the municipal public market to implement reforms in the operations and process so as to attain economic viability and  sustainability  in its operations.

We recommended that Management:

   a. direct the GSO to regularly monitor the expiration and renewal of  all motor vehicles registration to avoid penalties and fines for late/non- registration;


   b. Ensure that penalties  are  not  charged  to  government  coffers  and shouldered   instead   by   the   persons   responsible    for    late registration/renewal;


   c. facilitate transfer of ownership of the vehicles  which  are  not  yet under the name of the Municipality; and


   d. ensure that all insurable assets and properties  of  the  Municipality are adequately covered/insured.

We recommended that Management:

     a.  require  the  concerned  officers  and  employees  to  immediately settle/liquidate  their  outstanding  cash  advances  through   the submission of duly  accomplished  liquidation  reports,  otherwise, enforce  the  withholding  of  salary,  in  accordance   with   the provisions of COA Circular No. 97-002;

     b. stop the grant of additional cash advances to  all  personnel  with unliquidated cash advances until such time previous  cash  advances are fully settled, and see to it that officials and  employees  who seek transfer to other offices or those filing for  terminal  leave  are not given certificates of clearance until  their  balances are paid;

     c. request for the write-off of dormant accounts  in  accordance  with COA Circular No. 2016-005, if applicable;

     d. prepare and maintain complete and updated SLs and other  subsidiary records of the accounts presented in  the  FS  in  accordance  with Section 10 of the Manual on the NGAS for LGUs, Volume II;

     e. require the Disbursing Officer  to  observe  the  proper  handling, custody and disposition of cashbook to reflect the  actual  balance of cash advances as of a given date; and

     f. monitor and establish controls to ensure the timely liquidation  of cash advances through updated monthly ageing of the same to prevent accumulation of unliquidated cash  advances  and  ensure  that  the rules and regulations on the grant of cash advances are strictly observed.

We recommended that Management:          
require the Disbursing Officer/PCF Custodian and the Municipal Accountant to maintain the Petty Cash Fund under the imprest system and follow the procedures for petty cash disbursement in accordance with the New Government Accounting System (NGAS) Manual; 
strictly observe that only non-recurring, emergency and petty expenses are charged against PCF; 
prepare separate disbursement vouchers for recurring expenses and pay them through checks; 
set-up a separate special cash advance specifically for the payment of AICS disbursements and ensure that it is properly recorded, monitored and liquidated within the prescribed period; 
require the PCF Custodian to ensure that petty cash vouchers are properly filled out as to dates, boxes for appropriate checking and signatures; and 
require the PCF Custodian to see to it that approved estimates of petty expenses for one month were submitted for the initial cash advance and that all claims against PCF are supported with complete supporting documents to ensure their validity, propriety and legality.

We recommended that Management:          
direct the Municipal Accountant to coordinate with the Municipal Treasurer and depository bank for reconciling items which are doubtful in nature and exert effort to trace the said transactions; 
direct the Municipal Accountant to ensure that book reconciling items are recorded immediately once the supporting documents are available; 
verify the existence of the inactive/dormant deposit accounts and take the necessary action in case of misuse by the concerned accountable officer; and 
cause the closure of all inactive/dormant deposit accounts and the transfer of their balances to an active account.

We recommended that Management:          
require the concerned officers and employees to immediately settle/liquidate their outstanding cash advances through the submission of duly accomplished liquidation reports, otherwise, enforce the withholding of salary, in accordance with the provisions of COA Circular No. 97-002; 
stop the grant of additional cash advances for travel and training to all personnel with unliquidated cash advances and see to it that officials and employees who seek transfer to other offices or those filing for terminal leaves are not given certificates of clearance until their balances are paid; 
require the Municipal Accountant to prepare an adjusting entry for the proper classification of cash advances made for special purpose/time-bound undertakings by debiting “Advances to Special Disbursing Officers” account amounting to ₱1,136,568.81 and crediting “Advances for Payroll” account by the same amount, and ensure proper classification of accounts in succeeding grant and liquidation of cash advances; 
require the Disbursing Officer to observe the proper handling, custody and disposition of cashbook to reflect the actual balance of cash advances as of a given date; and 
monitor and establish controls to ensure the timely liquidation of cash advances through updated monthly ageing of the same to prevent accumulation of unliquidated cash advances and ensure that the rules and regulations on the grant of cash advances are strictly observed.

We recommended that Management require the: 
Establishment of a separate General Services Office (GSO) and stock room for proper storage of items of inventories; and require the coordination between the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer’s Office towards the implementation of the Perpetual Inventory Method in recording of supplies and materials and maintain the prescribed records to ensure proper accounting and promote better control in the receipt and issuance of supplies; 
Municipal Accountant and GSO-designate to maintain supplies ledger cards (SLC) and stock cards (SC), respectively, for each type of inventories and reconcile the accounting and property records periodically to bring these accounts into agreement; 
GSO-designate to maintain and submit the Summary of Supplies and Materials Issued (SSMI) together with the corresponding Requisition and Issue Slip (RIS) and Inventory Custodial Slips (ICS) for the issued supplies/goods; 
GSO-designate/Inventory Committee to prepare and submit a complete Report on the Physical Count of Inventories as of December 31, 2020 in order to determine the correctness of the recorded inventories in the books of accounts of the Municipality and to ensure that semestral count of Inventory items is promptly conducted and the corresponding report is submitted on time to the Audit Team; and 
Municipal Accountant to prepare an adjusting entry for the proper classification of goods for distribution to people affected by calamities/disasters by debiting “Welfare Goods for Distribution” account amounting to ₱455,300.00 and crediting “Food Supplies for Distribution” account by the same amount, and ensure proper classification of accounts in succeeding procurement of inventories.

We recommended that Management:          
instruct the Inventory Committee to include all properties in physical count and submit an updated and properly accomplished RPCPPE with all the needed information; 
designate one personnel each from the accounting and property offices who shall: maintain, on a full-time basis, the complete and updated PPE ledger and property cards for each category of PPE indicating adequate details/description of the properties such as model, serial number, location, cost and other information necessary to facilitate identification; and facilitate reconciliation of records; 
require the Municipal Accountant to prepare the necessary adjustments in the books to take up the completed projects in order to come up with the accurate balances of the CIP and appropriate asset accounts; 
strictly observe the use of Inventory Custodian Slip (ICS) by the Property Officer in the issuance of small tangible and semi-expendable items for proper monitoring and accountability; 
require the Municipal Accountant to identify other possible items needed to be excluded from the PPE account and make proper adjustments, if deemed necessary; 
require the Municipal Accountant to record in the books the lot numbers 621, 5227, 5214 and 770 with total market value of ₱12,409,442.00, which parcels of land were being used by the LGU as sites for Municipal Hall, SB Session Hall, Rural Health Unit and public market; 
instruct the Municipal Treasurer as the Property Custodian to maintain updated report of the LGU’s properties; and 
require the Municipal Assessor’s Office to facilitate the registration of the untitled land and/or transfer of title of the aforementioned parcels of lots in the name of the LGU with the Registry of Deeds.

We recommended that Management: 
strictly implement the anti-littering policy and require the barangays to formulate and implement an Anti-Littering ordinance at their level; 
encourage active participation of barangay officials to support the solid waste management program of the government by educating their respective constituents on the proper segregation of wastes; 
enforce sanctions on violators of the ordinances, laws and regulations pertaining to waste disposal; and 
intensify efforts to have the Ten-Year Solid Waste Management Plan finalized by the Solid Waste Management Board to hasten the approval of the plan by the National Solid Waste Management Commission.
